---
/*
  Lonboard iframe weight + UX prototype.

  This page exists ONLY so we can preview what an interactive lonboard map
  embedded as an iframe feels like — on a deployed Cloudflare branch, on
  mobile, on slow connections — before deciding whether to wire this
  pattern into build-content.py site-wide.

  The map asset (`public/maps-demo/test-map.html`) is ~3.7 MB raw /
  ~980 KB gzipped — the actual cost of one lonboard map's inlined JS bundle.
  `loading="lazy"` means it doesn't download until you scroll near it.

  Remove this file and `public/maps-demo/` once the decision is made.
*/
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---
<BaseLayout title="Lonboard iframe prototype">
  <article class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
    <header class="mb-10 not-prose border-b border-border pb-6">
      <p class="text-xs font-semibold text-accent uppercase tracking-[0.14em]">
        Prototype
      </p>
      <h1 class="mt-3 text-4xl md:text-5xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-text leading-[1.1]">
        Lonboard interactive iframe
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-4 text-lg text-muted leading-relaxed">
        Weight + UX prototype for option #2 (interactive iframe) on the
        question of how to surface lonboard widget outputs statically.
      </p>
    </header>

    <h2>The numbers</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>This page's HTML</strong>: trivial — same as any lesson page.</li>
      <li><strong>Map asset (iframe src)</strong>: ~3.7&nbsp;MB raw, ~980&nbsp;KB over the wire (gzipped).</li>
      <li>
        <strong>When does it load?</strong> Not until you scroll near the
        iframe. The page itself opens at full speed; the cost only hits
        when (and if) the student gets to that section.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>What's it actually like?</h2>
    <p>
      Scroll down. The map below is a synthetic 2-point dataset wrapped in
      lonboard's default ScatterplotLayer + bundled deck.gl JS. Identical
      bundle weight to any real lonboard map — what changes between real
      maps is just the data payload, not the JS bundle.
    </p>
    <p>
      Try panning, zooming with mousewheel, and on mobile pinching. That's
      what students get vs. a flat PNG screenshot.
    </p>

    <div class="my-12">
      <figure class="output-figure output-iframe">
        <iframe
          src="/maps-demo/test-map.html"
          loading="lazy"
          title="Interactive lonboard map"
          class="lonboard-frame"
          width="100%"
          height="500"
          frameborder="0"
        ></iframe>
        <figcaption>
          Lonboard ScatterplotLayer, embedded as iframe. Lazy-loaded.
        </figcaption>
      </figure>
    </div>

    <h2>What would the production pattern look like?</h2>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <code>build-content.py</code> (in <code>--execute</code> mode) detects
        cells whose output is a <code>application/vnd.jupyter.widget-view+json</code>
        MIME type backed by a lonboard widget model.
      </li>
      <li>
        For each such cell, re-execute just enough to get the
        <code>Map</code> object back, then call
        <code>m.to_html(path)</code> to dump a self-contained HTML file.
      </li>
      <li>
        Save the HTML to a stable, non-gitignored location
        (e.g. <code>public/maps/&lt;lesson&gt;-&lt;cell&gt;.html</code>) so
        the no-execute Cloudflare build path can serve it without re-running
        Python.
      </li>
      <li>
        Emit an <code>&lt;iframe&gt;</code> in the lesson markdown pointing
        at that file, with <code>loading="lazy"</code>.
      </li>
    </ol>

    <h2>Open questions</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Storage location</strong> — currently <code>public/lesson-assets/</code>
        is wiped by every <code>build-content.py</code> run. The map HTMLs
        need a different home, OR build-content.py needs a "preserve
        subdir" mechanism, OR we accept that maps are re-generated on every
        execute build.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Multiple maps per page</strong> — each is its own bundle,
        no sharing. A page with 5 maps = ~5&nbsp;MB. Worth setting a limit
        or warning?
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Fallback for failed executions</strong> — if
        <code>m.to_html()</code> errors, what do we show? Code block only?
        A note?
      </li>
    </ul>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
